st, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"about 1309–after 1365":"circa 1309–na 1365","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1309–1365":"1309–1365","about 1309":"circa 1309","1305":"1305","1365":"1365","21 September 1348":"21 september 1348","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","after 1365":"na 1365","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"about 1309–after 1365":"about 1309–after 1365","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1309–1365":"1309–1365","about 1309":"about 1309","1305":"1305","1365":"1365","21 September 1348":"21 September 1348","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","after 1365":"after 1365","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sherburne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from any of several places called with Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘bright, clear’ + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’, including Sherburn in Elmet (Yorkshire), Sherburn (East Yorkshire, Durham), Shirburn (Oxfordshire), Sherborne (Dorset, Gloucestershire), Sherborne Saint John, Monk Sherborne (Hampshire), Sherbourne (Warwickshire), Sherbourne in Albury (Surrey), and Sherborne in Litton (Somerset). This surname is now rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Sherburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Sherburne  ."]},{"name":"Sherbon","meanings":["English: variant of   Sherburne   with loss of the second <i>-r-</i> by dissimilation. This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Sherburne was born about 1309, in Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir William Clifton on 21 September 1348. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1365."},"et":{"about 1309–after 1365":"umbes 1309–pärast 1365","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1309–1365":"1309–1365","about 1309":"umbes 1309","1305":"1305","1365":"1365","21 September 1348":"21. september 1348","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","after 1365":"pärast 1365","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1309–after 1365":"noin 1309–1365 jälkeen","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1309–1365":"1309–1365","about 1309":"noin 1309","1305":"1305","1365":"1365","21 September 1348":"21. syyskuuta 1348","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","after 1365":"1365 jälkeen","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1309–after 1365":"environ 1309–après 1365","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1309–1365":"1309–1365",